<p class="">I am sorry, no.<p></p> The present Minister of Labour said this in that debate: <blockquote><q>"What argument have they"—</q></blockquote> That is, the National Government— <blockquote><q>"to persuade the young men to fight, except merely in another squalid attempt to defend themselves against the redistribution of international swag?"<span id="vol346_col2139" class="cross-reference" data-house-id="1" data-column-number="2139" data-volume-number="346">—[OFFICIAL REPORT, 4th May, 1939; Vol. 346, c. 2139.]</span></q></blockquote> That was four months before the war started. Four days later, Mr. Neil Maclean, the then Member for Govan, said: <blockquote><q>"This conscription Bill is a Bill which I for one shall advise every young man of 19 and 20 to refuse to accept"—</q></blockquote></p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
